#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:126
msgid "## Sticky Notes"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:127
msgid ""
"Give each learner two sticky notes of different colours, e.g., yellow and blue.\n"
"If someone has completed an exercise, they put the blue sticky note on their laptop;\n"
"if they run into a problem and need help, the put up the yellow one.  This is better\n"
"than having people raise their hands because:"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:132
msgid ""
"*  it's more discreet (which means they're more likely to actually do it),"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:133
msgid "*  they can keep working while their flag is raised, and"
msgstr ""

# unordered list
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:134
msgid ""
"*  the instructor can quickly see from the front of the room what state the "
"class is in."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:136
msgid ""
"Sometimes a yellow sticky involves a technical problem that takes a bit\n"
"more time to solve.  To prevent this issue slowing down the whole\n"
"class too much, you could use the occasion to take the small break you\n"
"had planned to take a bit later, giving the helper(s) time to fix the\n"
"problem."
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:142
msgid ""
"Remind learners frequently about using their sticky notes, or they (and you)"
" will forget."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:144
msgid "> ## Accessibility of Sticky Notes"
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:145
msgid ""
"> We strongly encourage you to get sticky notes in colors other than red and"
" green, "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:146
msgid ""
"> as we have found that some learners (not to mention helpers and "
"instructors!) "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:147
msgid ""
"> may have colorblindness and thus cannot properly ask for/give help this "
"way. "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:148
msgid ""
"> Alternate ideas are to use differently-shaped sticky notes (stars and "
"squares, "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:149
msgid ""
"> thumbs up that can be turned into thumbs down stickies), or to use one "
"sticky note "
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:150
msgid "> as a flag for help."
msgstr ""

# blockquote, which can be cascaded
#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:153
msgid "> ## Practice Teaching"
msgstr ""

#: instructor-training/_episodes/14-live.md:154
msgid ""
">\n"
"> Teach 3 minutes of your chosen lesson episode using live coding to one or two\n"
"> fellow trainees, then swap and watch while the other person(s) live codes for\n"
"> you. (For this exercise, your peers will not \"code-along\", but will instead observe and give feedback.)\n"
">\n"
"> Explain in advance to your fellow trainee(s) what you will be teaching\n"
"> and what the learners you teach it to are expected to be familiar with.\n"
">\n"
"> **Don't record this exercise.** Give each other feedback\n"
"> using the 2x2 rubric we discussed previously and enter the feedback\n"
"> you received in the Etherpad.\n"
">\n"
"> This exercise should take about 25 minutes.  "
msgstr ""

